question:
In the diagram, $PT$ is parallel to $QR.$ What is the measure of $\angle PQR$ in degrees?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(10,0),MidArrow);
draw((10,0)--(20,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(-7,10)--(7,10)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-5,10)--(7,10),MidArrow);
label("$x^{\circ}$",(-6,10),SE);
label("$2x^{\circ}$",(7,10),SW);
label("$128^{\circ}$",(10,0),NE);
label("$P$",(-7,10),N);
label("$T$",(7,10),N);
label("$R$",(10,0),S);
label("$Q$",(0,0),S);
[/asy]
# known:
1. **Angles formed by a transversal of parallel lines**: When a line cuts two parallel lines, corresponding angles are equal and interior angles on the same side of the transversal are supplementary (sum to \(180^\circ\)).
2. **Exterior angle of a triangle**: An exterior angle of a triangle equals the sum of the two non-adjacent interior angles. This helps relate an angle at \(R\) outside \(\triangle PQR\) to angles at \(P\) and \(Q\).
# Answer:

ref_solution:
Since $PT$ and $RQ$ are parallel, then $2x^\circ=128^\circ,$ so $x=64,$ so $\angle TPQ=64^\circ.$

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(10,0),MidArrow);
draw((10,0)--(20,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(-7,10)--(7,10)--(10,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-5,10)--(7,10),MidArrow);
label("$x^{\circ}$",(-6,10),SE);
label("$2x^{\circ}$",(7,10),SW);
label("$128^{\circ}$",(10,0),NE);
label("$P$",(-7,10),N);
label("$T$",(7,10),N);
label("$R$",(10,0),S);
label("$Q$",(0,0),S);
[/asy]

Since $PT$ and $QR$ are parallel, then $\angle TPQ$ and $\angle PQR$ are supplementary. Thus, $\angle PQR + 64^\circ = 180^\circ,$ so $\angle PQR = \boxed{116} \text{ degrees}.$

